Here\'92s how V4 (and the wider system) line up with those self-help author-trust ideas, and what would make it better.\
What V4 / the system already do\
Principle	Current state\
Credibility / expertise	Author YAML has bio_80w, domains, tones, metadata (background, current job, specific_struggles, strengths). That\'92s enough to describe a credible, consistent author.\
Author as a person	One author per book: author_id in plan/manifest, chosen from persona\'92s pool. Same author drives cover, voice, and (where used) POV.\
Name and \'93expertise\'94 in intros	A0: \'93This book was written by \{author_display_name\}\'94. A1: one generic line, \{author['display_name']\} brings expertise to help you navigate \{topic\} with both wisdom and compassion. So the listener hears who the author is and that they \'93bring expertise,\'94 but nothing more specific.\
Stories and examples	Story injection is persona-aware; story bank is written using author metadata (e.g. docs/CONTENT_TEAM_STORY_WRITING_SPEC.md, docs/AUTHOR_METADATA_STORY_WRITING_GUIDE.md). So the system is set up to use author-consistent, relatable detail in stories.\
Voice / narrator	Author\'92s voice_profile_id and narrator are used for TTS and credits, so the \'93voice\'94 is tied to the author.\
Belief / authenticity	HUMAN_VALIDATION.md and voice-pack docs stress \'93does this sound like someone who actually believes this?\'94 and avoiding \'93sounds AI\'94 \'97 i.e. the goal is there, but it\'92s a content/quality bar, not a structural one.\
So: we do address \'93who the author is\'94 in a basic way (name, one expertise line, voice, cover, POV when used), but we don\'92t yet fully use the author data we have to build trust in the way the self-help advice suggests.\
