The same sentence is used for every author (only display_name and topic change). We don\'92t yet \'93use clear, human-sounding voice and personality\'94 or \'93relevant life experience\'94 in the intro \'97 no first-person hint, no \'93why I care about this,\'94 no domain-specific line (e.g. peer vs clinician vs educator).\
Author vs persona in A1 context\
In intro_conclusion_builder.py, the A1 template context uses the persona\'92s bio_80w and struggles (audience), not the author\'92s bio/credentials. So the intro is built around \'93who this is for,\'94 not \'93who is speaking and why they\'92re qualified.\'94\
No AI transparency\
There\'92s no listener-facing disclaimer or \'93curated for your benefit\'94 / \'93AI-assisted\'94 note in A0, A1, or metadata. So \'93thoughtful about AI transparency\'94 isn\'92t implemented in the product yet.\
Author and body prose\
V4 assembly is persona/topic-driven (and story injection is persona-aware). It\'92s not clear that author_id shapes section choice or framing so the body feels like one consistent author\'92s voice. So \'93authentic personal voice\'94 and \'93consistent in tone and values\'94 may be only partly addressed.\
What to do better (concrete)\
A. Use author backstory in intros\
In A1 (and optionally A0), pull from the author YAML: e.g. bio_80w or a short credential line (2\'963 sentences).\
Don\'92t just say \'93written by X\'94 and \'93brings expertise\'94; say why they\'92re qualified (theoretical credentials, relevant experience, specialty) in natural language.\
