\fs32 \cf0 \cb7 we have this, but plan should  do this: Here's how output to the platform works and where titles and descriptions come from.\
Does it write titles and descriptions?\
Yes. The pipeline produces titles and descriptions and writes them into:\
Series JSON (e.g. series_data/phoenix/\{series_id\}.json)\
Per-book manifests (e.g. under the series output dir)\
Google Play Books CSV (export file you use for upload)\
It does not call Google Play / Spotify / Apple APIs. \'93Output to back platform\'94 = generating files (metadata + CSV) that you then upload or feed into another system.\
Where titles and descriptions are set\
1. Series-level (subtitle + description)\
tools/series_metadata_generator.py\
generate_series_google_play_metadata(series_metadata) builds the blob that becomes \'93Google Play\'94 metadata for the series.\
Series subtitle: Uses series_metadata.get("series_subtitle") when present (V4 plan/brand). Otherwise falls back to "Complete Series (N books)" (see lines 206\'96209, 243\'96244).\
Series description: Built by generate_series_description(series_name, series_subtitle, persona, topic, num_books) (lines 13\'9686). That description uses the series subtitle as the second line (line 40\'9641) and is capped at 5000 chars for Google Play.\
So series subtitle and series description are both \'93written\'94 (generated) here and stored in the series\'92 google_play metadata.\
2. Where that metadata is attached\
tools/phoenix_series_builder.py\
After creating the series, it calls generate_series_google_play_metadata(series) and sets series["google_play"] (lines 373\'96374).\
It persists the series (including google_play) to series_data/phoenix/\{series_id\}.json (line 363).\
For each book manifest it passes series_metadata and sets manifest["series"]["series_subtitle"] from series.get("series_subtitle") (lines 462\'96463).\
So titles and descriptions are written into the in-repo series JSON and manifests; they are not sent to the internet by this code.\
3. Per-book title and subtitle\
Phoenix series builder sets each book\'92s book_title and book_subtitle in the book config/manifest (from plan overrides or V4 title planner / build_book_subtitle).\
Those end up in the manifest as book_title and book_subtitle (see e.g. lines 352\'96357, 407, 428).\
tools/generate_google_play_csv_enhanced.py\
Reads manifests and series metadata.\
Book row: Uses manifest.get("book_title") and manifest.get("book_subtitle") for the CSV columns "Title" and "Subtitle" (e.g. lines 294\'96295, 398\'96399, 441\'96442, 502\'96503).\
Series row (if present): Uses series_metadata["google_play"]["subtitle"] and description for the series line in the CSV (lines 101\'96103, 129\'96130).\
So both book titles/subtitles and series subtitle/description are written into the CSV that is the \'93output to back platform\'94 for Google Play.\
End-to-end flow (titles + descriptions)\
Phoenix series builder (optionally with V4 plan + brand) produces:\
Series JSON with series_subtitle, description, and google_play (subtitle + enhanced description).\
Per-book manifests with book_title, book_subtitle, and series info.\
Series metadata generator is used by the builder to generate the series description and to set the series subtitle in google_play (using V4 series_subtitle when present).\
Google Play CSV generator reads those manifests and series JSON and writes a CSV with:\
Title, Subtitle, Series Title, Description, etc., for books and series.\
That CSV is the \'93output to back platform\'94 \'97 you (or another process) upload it to Google Play; the repo does not push to an API.\
So: yes, it writes titles and descriptions \'97 into series metadata, manifests, and the Google Play CSV. The \'93back platform\'94 output is file-based (JSON + CSV), not live API writes.\
